You're referring to the initialization string in C++.

In C++, the `std::cout` object has an internal buffer that stores the output. When you use `std::cout`, it appends the output to this buffer. However, when the buffer is full or when you use `std::endl` (which flushes the buffer), the contents of the buffer are sent to the output stream (usually the console).

To see the initialization string, you can use the following code:

```cpp
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    std::cout << "Hello, World!" << std::flush;
    return 0;
}
```

In this code, `std::flush` is used to force the output to be sent to the console immediately, rather than being buffered. This will display "Hello, World!" on the console.

